javaslang.collection

Class Stream.Cons<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • javaslang.collection.Stream.AbstractStream<T>
      • javaslang.collection.Stream.Cons<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - Component type of the Stream.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Iterable<T>, IntFunction<T>, Seq<T>, Stream<T>, Traversable<T>, TraversableOnce<T>
    Enclosing interface:
    Stream<T>

    public static final class Stream.Cons<T>
extends Stream.AbstractStream<T>
implements Serializable
    Non-empty Stream, consisting of a head, a tail and an optional AutoCloseable.
    Since:
    1.1.0

    Serialized Form

      • appendSelf

        public Stream<T> appendSelf(Function<? super Stream<T>,? extends Stream<T>> mapper)
        Description copied from interface: Stream
        Appends itself to the end of stream with mapper function.

        Example:

        Well known scala code for Fibonacci infinite sequence 

         
 val fibs:Stream[Int] = 0 #:: 1 #:: (fibs zip fibs.tail).map{ t => t._1 + t._2 }
        can be transformed to 
         
 Stream.of(0, 1).appendSelf(self -> self.zip(self.tail()).map(t -> t._1 + t._2));
        Specified by:
        appendSelf in interface Stream<T>
        Parameters:
        mapper - an mapper
        Returns:
        a new Stream

      • subsequence

        public Stream<T> subsequence(int beginIndex,
                             int endIndex)
        Description copied from interface: Seq

        Returns a Seq that is a subsequence of this. The subsequence begins with the element at the specified index and extends to the element at index endIndex - 1.

        Examples: 
         
 List.of(1, 2, 3, 4).substring(1, 3) = List.of(2, 3)
 List.of(1, 2, 3, 4).substring(0, 4) = List.of(1, 2, 3, 4)
 List.of(1, 2, 3, 4).substring(2, 2) = List.empty()
        Specified by:
        subsequence in interface Seq<T>
        Specified by:
        subsequence in interface Stream<T>
        Parameters:
        beginIndex - the beginning index, inclusive
        endIndex - the end index, exclusive
        Returns:
        the specified subsequence

      • take

        public Stream<T> take(int n)
        Description copied from interface: Traversable
        Takes the first n elements of this or all elements, if this length < n.

        The result is equivalent to sublist(0, max(0, min(length(), n))) but does not throw if n < 0 or n > length().

        In the case of n < 0 the empty instance is returned, in the case of n > length() this is returned.

        Specified by:
        take in interface Seq<T>
        Specified by:
        take in interface Stream<T>
        Specified by:
        take in interface Traversable<T>
        Parameters:
        n - The number of elements to take.
        Returns:
        A new instance consisting the first n elements of this or all elements, if this has less than n elements.
